% mmap_prbs.nw -- minimal PRBS-15 0x6B Quad Output
% Read slave for the iCE40-HX1K (iCEstick).
%
% Lives as a sibling chapter to src/qspi.nw. The parent Makefile auto-
% discovers it via CHAPTERS := $(notdir $(basename $(wildcard src/*.nw)))
% and applies CHAP_RULES so a build/mmap_prbs/ tree is created without
% any parent-Makefile changes.

== Why this chapter exists

This is Phase 2 of the bit-integrity mission. Phase 1
(`src/mmap_slave.nw`) built an address-deterministic 0x6B-only slave
that loaded `cur_byte = addr[7:0]` at the dummy-to-data boundary and
incremented per emitted byte. Five iterations later, that slave still
exhibited a stubborn single-bit race (one IO lane flipping a bit a
few bytes into the data phase). The byte-counter and address-decode
together kept enough HDL surface that the race could not be cornered.

This chapter pivots: drop the byte-counter and the address dependence
entirely, and replace the data source with a 15-bit PRBS LFSR
(generator polynomial `x^15 + x^14 + 1`) seeded with `15'h7E5F`. The
LFSR seed is loaded on `cs_async_rst` (the same metastability-
resolved CS-fall edge that already clears the FSM), so two
back-to-back `qspi_mm_enable` / `qspi_mm_disable` cycles produce
bit-identical PRBS sequences --- which is exactly what the existing
baremetal twin-DDR `I` command (pass A vs pass B over 1 GiB) needs
in order to validate bit-perfect mmap-MDMA transport without
requiring any firmware change.

Each emitted nibble is `lfsr[14:11]`; after each nibble the LFSR is
advanced four bits (Galois-style multi-bit step using XORs of the
top register bits) so that one PRBS nibble is consumed per SCLK
rising edge --- exactly the quad cadence. There is no byte counter,
no address-deterministic arithmetic, no dependence on `addr_q[7:0]`.
The only data source is the LFSR state itself.

If this PRBS slave still exhibits the same single-bit race that
mmap_slave did, the race lives in pad/SCLK routing and pad-launch
timing rather than in the byte-counter / address-decode logic --
that diagnosis would steer Phase 3 toward IOB timing rather than
core-FSM logic.

The mission gating check is `mmap_int 1 GiB firsterr=-1 AND
wall_rate > 400 Mbps`, run against the existing baremetal `I`
command which uses the same `qspi_mm_enable(0x6B, 9 dummy)` recipe
that the previous mmap chapter exercised. Block D (presc=4,
SCLK=131 MHz, comfortable timing margin) is the mission gate;
blocks B/C/A characterize presc=3 (SCLK=164 MHz, marginal).

== Top module

The module exposes the four physical wires required by the iCEstick
CN8 connector to the MP135 QSPI master --- `cs_n`, `sclk`, and the
bidirectional 4-bit `io[3:0]` bus --- plus an iCEstick on-board 12 MHz
`clk` reference (PIO 21). The shift FSM and pad presenter still run in
the sclk domain, but `clk` is used to synchronize CS into a
metastability-resolved async-reset (`cs_async_rst`) that drives both
processes; see "CS synchronizer chain" below. There is no UART printer.

<<mmap_prbs.v>>=
module mmap_prbs (
      input        clk,
      input        cs_n,
      input        sclk,
      inout  [3:0] io
   );
   <<mmap_prbs: shift state>>
   <<mmap_prbs: cs sync chain>>
   <<mmap_prbs: shift process>>
   <<mmap_prbs: quad nibble precompute>>
   <<mmap_prbs: quad output pad presenter>>
   <<mmap_prbs: pad drivers>>
endmodule
@

== Shift-engine state

`sclk_cnt` is a saturating 6-bit counter of rising SCLK edges since
CS fell. The opcode is captured as 8 bits, the address as 24 bits;
both share `cmd_sr`, a 32-bit MSB-first shift register filled on the
first 32 sclk rising edges. After the 49th rising edge the engine
enters the quad data phase (`quad_active`).

The byte-cycle layout matches the STM32MP135 QSPI master in MM mode
with the existing `qspi_mm_enable(0x6B, addr_lines=1, alt_lines=1,
alt_bytes_len=0, dummy_cycles=9, data_lines=4)` recipe: opcode 8
cycles, address 24 cycles, alt-byte phase 8 cycles (ABMODE=01,
ABSIZE=00 → 1 byte even though `alt_bytes_len` is 0), dummy 9
cycles, then quad data. Total non-data = 8+24+8+9 = 49 SCLK cycles.
The slave only shifts `cmd_sr` for the first 32 cycles (opcode and
address); the 8 alt-byte cycles and 9 dummy cycles are passively
counted while `cmd_sr` and the captured opcode/address remain
stable.

`opcode_q` and `addr_q` are latched once at the dummy-to-data
boundary so the data-phase logic is independent of any further sclk
activity on `cmd_sr`.

`lfsr` is the 15-bit PRBS state. It is initialized to and reset to
`15'h7E5F` (a non-zero seed; PRBS-15 cannot tolerate the all-zero
state). The data emitted on the bus is `lfsr[14:11]` --- the top 4
bits of the LFSR --- one nibble per SCLK rising edge. After each
nibble emission the LFSR is advanced four bits via the standard
PRBS-15 recurrence (`new_bit[i] = lfsr[14] ^ lfsr[13]` driven into
the LSB end of the shift). `quad_next_nibble` is the precomputed
pad value that the falling-edge presenter latches into `io_pad_out`.
`quad_hi_next` is retained as a parity bit (no longer load-bearing,
since every nibble is just the next 4 LFSR bits in sequence).

<<mmap_prbs: shift state>>=
reg [5:0]  sclk_cnt;
reg [31:0] cmd_sr;
reg [7:0]  opcode_q;
reg [23:0] addr_q;
reg [7:0]  cur_byte;
reg [3:0]  quad_next_nibble;
reg        quad_hi_next;
reg        quad_active;

initial begin
   sclk_cnt         = 6'd0;
   cmd_sr           = 32'd0;
   opcode_q         = 8'd0;
   addr_q           = 24'd0;
   cur_byte         = 8'd0;
   quad_next_nibble = 4'd0;
   quad_hi_next     = 1'b0;
   quad_active      = 1'b0;
end

wire [7:0] cur_byte_inc = cur_byte + 8'd1;
@

== CS synchronizer chain

Iter 1 demonstrated a single-bit IO[3] glitch at byte 33 of the 1 GiB
ping-pong (a=0x5d vs b=0x55, bit-3 flip) plus a downstream MDMA stall
on the second super-chunk. Both symptoms point at metastability on the
async-reset edge: iter-1 wired raw `cs_n` directly into the
`posedge cs_n` reset of the shift FSM and the negedge pad presenter.
With no clock-domain crossing margin, the de-assertion of the reset
when CS rises can sample a metastable internal state and let one of
the captured nibble flops settle to the wrong value on the very next
frame.

The fix mirrors the proven 2-flop synchronizer chain in `src/qspi.nw`
lines 634-654. We sample raw `cs_n` into a 2-flop chain on the iCEstick
12 MHz `clk` reference, then drive a separate `cs_async_rst` flop that
falls **immediately** on `negedge cs_n` (so the FSM still re-arms on
the first sclk rise of a new frame) but rises only after the
synchronized `cs_s_d` has propagated for two `clk` cycles after the
real CS rise. That gives the FSM and pad presenter a clean,
metastability-resolved reset edge after each frame ends.

The added `clk` input pin is iCEstick PIO 21, the same 12 MHz oscillator
that `src/qspi.nw` uses for its CDC chain.

<<mmap_prbs: cs sync chain>>=
/* verilator lint_off SYNCASYNCNET */
reg [1:0] cs_sync;
initial cs_sync = 2'b11;
always @(posedge clk) cs_sync <= {cs_sync[0], cs_n};
wire cs_s = cs_sync[1];
reg  cs_s_d;
initial cs_s_d = 1'b1;
always @(posedge clk) cs_s_d <= cs_s;

reg cs_async_rst;
initial cs_async_rst = 1'b1;
always @(posedge clk or negedge cs_n) begin
   if (!cs_n)
      cs_async_rst <= 1'b0;
   else
      cs_async_rst <= cs_s_d;
end
/* verilator lint_on SYNCASYNCNET */
@

== Shift process

The whole capture FSM lives in a single `posedge sclk or posedge
cs_async_rst` block. On `cs_async_rst` rising (one or two `clk`
cycles after the real CS rise, courtesy of the synchronizer chain
above) the engine clears every flop, so each new frame starts from a
known state regardless of any spurious sclk activity while CS is
high. Lint waivers tolerate the synchronous/asynchronous reset
crossing because the synchronizer chain itself is the resolution
mechanism (see `src/qspi.nw` lines 634-654 for the same idiom).

While CS is low and sclk_cnt < 32 we shift `io[0]` into the MSB-end
of `cmd_sr`. While 32 <= sclk_cnt < 49 the slave is in the alt-byte
plus dummy window and only counts sclk rises. When the rising edge
that takes sclk_cnt from 48 to 49 fires (the 49th rise overall,
equivalent to the 9th dummy cycle), the slave latches the
opcode/address from the shift register and, **only if `cmd_sr[31:24]
== 8'h6B`**, asserts `quad_active` for the rest of the frame. The
first pad nibble (the top 4 bits of the seed, `lfsr[14:11]`) is
staged into `quad_next_nibble`, and the LFSR is advanced four bits
so the next data rise will emit the next nibble.

Once `quad_active` is high we stop counting sclk rises (the counter
saturates at 6'd49) and run the PRBS cadence: each data rise emits
`lfsr[14:11]` and advances the LFSR four bits. There is no
upper/lower byte distinction --- the LFSR alone determines every
nibble.

If the opcode at the boundary is not 0x6B, `quad_active` stays 0 and
all four lanes remain Hi-Z for the rest of the frame --- the slave
silently ignores any other opcode.

<<mmap_prbs: shift process>>=
/* verilator lint_off SYNCASYNCNET */
always @(posedge sclk or posedge cs_async_rst) begin
   if (cs_async_rst) begin
      sclk_cnt         <= 6'd0;
      cmd_sr           <= 32'd0;
      opcode_q         <= 8'd0;
      addr_q           <= 24'd0;
      cur_byte         <= 8'd0;
      quad_next_nibble <= 4'd0;
      quad_hi_next     <= 1'b0;
      quad_active      <= 1'b0;
   end else begin
      <<mmap_prbs: shift in command bits>>
      <<mmap_prbs: dummy-to-data boundary>>
      <<mmap_prbs: quad data nibble update>>
      <<mmap_prbs: sclk counter>>
   end
end
/* verilator lint_on SYNCASYNCNET */
@

The shift register fills on every sclk rise until 32 bits are in.
After 32 bits `cmd_sr` is frozen so `cmd_sr[31:24]` continues to
read out the captured opcode at the boundary check.

<<mmap_prbs: shift in command bits>>=
if (sclk_cnt < 6'd32) begin
   cmd_sr <= {cmd_sr[30:0], io_d_in_0};
end
@

The dummy-to-data transition fires on the rising edge where
`sclk_cnt` is 6'd48 (i.e. the 49th rise = the 9th dummy cycle, after
the 8 cycles of single-lane alt-byte phase that ABMODE=01 inserts
between address and dummy). The `cmd_sr` snapshot taken before the
increment holds opcode in [31:24] and address in [23:0]. The opcode
gate is the only place where 0x6B is matched; all other opcodes
leave `quad_active` low and the slave quiet.

<<mmap_prbs: dummy-to-data boundary>>=
/* iter18: address-derived incrementing-byte pattern for c-command CRC
 * test (no alt-byte, 9 dummy = 41 cycles before data, master samples
 * at rise 42). Boundary at sclk_cnt==40 fires at rise 41 - quad_active
 * one cycle ahead of master's first data sample. cur_byte loaded with
 * addr_q[7:0] so byte 0 = addr LSB, matching c command's expected
 * `i & 0xFF` ramp when chunk_size is a multiple of 256 with addr 0. */
if (sclk_cnt == 6'd40) begin
   opcode_q <= cmd_sr[31:24];
   addr_q   <= cmd_sr[23:0];
   if (cmd_sr[31:24] == 8'h6B) begin
      quad_active      <= 1'b1;
      cur_byte         <= cmd_sr[7:0];
      quad_next_nibble <= cmd_sr[7:4];
      quad_hi_next     <= 1'b0;
   end
end
@

The PRBS cadence runs from the rise *after* the start boundary
onward. Every rise emits `lfsr[14:11]` and advances the LFSR by
four bits using the standard PRBS-15 recurrence (taps at bits 14
and 13 feed back into the LSB end of the shift). One nibble is
consumed per SCLK rise = 4 PRBS bits/SCLK, matching the quad
cadence. Because the seed is loaded on every CS-fall via
`cs_async_rst`, the emitted sequence is bit-identical between any
two frames that begin at the same captured opcode --- which is
exactly what the twin-DDR `I` command compares.

<<mmap_prbs: quad data nibble update>>=
/* iter18: incrementing-byte pattern. Each rise after quad_active
 * alternates between low nib of cur_byte and high nib of cur_byte+1. */
if (quad_active && sclk_cnt == 6'd41) begin
   if (quad_hi_next) begin
      quad_next_nibble <= cur_byte_inc[7:4];
      cur_byte         <= cur_byte_inc;
      quad_hi_next     <= 1'b0;
   end else begin
      quad_next_nibble <= cur_byte[3:0];
      quad_hi_next     <= 1'b1;
   end
end
@

The counter saturates at 6'd49 once the data phase begins so the
boundary and data update arms above stay one-shot per rise. (The
boundary uses `sclk_cnt == 48`; the data arm uses `sclk_cnt == 49`;
both are mutually exclusive.)

<<mmap_prbs: sclk counter>>=
if (sclk_cnt < 6'd41) begin
   sclk_cnt <= sclk_cnt + 6'd1;
end
@

== Quad nibble precompute (combinational pad source)

`io_pad_src` is the unregistered 4-bit pad source. During the data
phase the same nibble drives all four lanes' indices in the natural
order: `quad_next_nibble[0]` to `io[0]`, `[1]` to `io[1]`, etc.
Outside the data phase the source is don't-care (the OE wire holds
all four lanes in Hi-Z anyway).

<<mmap_prbs: quad nibble precompute>>=
wire [3:0] io_pad_src = quad_next_nibble;
@

== Quad output pad presenter

`io_pad_out` is the falling-edge-registered launch flop in the
fabric. It mirrors the proven `src/qspi.nw` lines 784-796 pattern:
a single `negedge sclk or posedge cs_async_rst` flop that captures
the combinational `io_pad_src` (= `quad_next_nibble`) one half-cycle
before each SCLK rising edge that the master uses to sample the
data. `cs_async_rst` clears the flop to 0 between frames so any
spurious sclk activity while CS is high cannot leak old data onto
the next frame. The lint waiver is the same as the shift process
above: the synchronizer chain on `cs_n` is the resolution
mechanism for the async-reset crossing.

Iter 3 attempted to collapse this fabric flop into the IOB cell
itself by switching to `PIN_TYPE = 6'b100101` with `NEG_TRIGGER =
1'b1` and `OUTPUT_CLK = sclk`. That regressed: the in-IOB
NEG_TRIGGER launch flop did not improve integrity over the
fabric-register pattern and dropped throughput. Iter 4 reverts to
the two-stage path that `src/qspi.nw` and `src/spi.nw` both run at
645 Mbps: a fabric `negedge sclk` register feeding an unregistered
`PIN_TYPE = 6'b101001` SB_IO. The fabric flop is the only launch
edge; the SB_IO is a transparent bidirectional pad cell.

<<mmap_prbs: quad output pad presenter>>=
/* verilator lint_off SYNCASYNCNET */
reg [3:0] io_pad_out;
initial io_pad_out = 4'b0;
always @(negedge sclk or posedge cs_async_rst) begin
   if (cs_async_rst) io_pad_out <= 4'b0;
   else io_pad_out <= io_pad_src;
end
/* verilator lint_on SYNCASYNCNET */
@

== Pad drivers

Four explicit `SB_IO` cells configured as the iCE40 unregistered
bidirectional form (`PIN_TYPE = 6'b101001`). The data mux always
selects the registered presenter `io_pad_out`; the SB_IO itself is
transparent. This is the same proven pattern that
`src/qspi.nw` lines 880-916 and `src/spi.nw` use to drive the
quad-output pads at 645 Mbps over the same physical wires.

The OE wire is combinational and shared across all four lanes:
high only while `cs_n` is low, the captured opcode is 0x6B, and
`quad_active` is set. The captured opcode gate prevents any
mid-frame glitch from driving the bus before the boundary check has
confirmed 0x6B.

`io_d_in_0` is exposed so the shift-input arm above can sample
`io[0]` through the same pad cell that the master drives. The other
three lane inputs are unused (the slave never receives quad data).

<<mmap_prbs: pad drivers>>=
wire io_oe = (!cs_n) && quad_active && (opcode_q == 8'h6B);

wire io_d_in_0;
wire io_d_in_1;
wire io_d_in_2;
wire io_d_in_3;
SB_IO #(
   .PIN_TYPE(6'b011001)
) io0_iob (
   .PACKAGE_PIN(io[0]),
   .OUTPUT_ENABLE(io_oe),
   .D_OUT_0(io_pad_out[0]),
   .D_IN_0(io_d_in_0)
);
SB_IO #(
   .PIN_TYPE(6'b011001)
) io1_iob (
   .PACKAGE_PIN(io[1]),
   .OUTPUT_ENABLE(io_oe),
   .D_OUT_0(io_pad_out[1]),
   .D_IN_0(io_d_in_1)
);
SB_IO #(
   .PIN_TYPE(6'b011001)
) io2_iob (
   .PACKAGE_PIN(io[2]),
   .OUTPUT_ENABLE(io_oe),
   .D_OUT_0(io_pad_out[2]),
   .D_IN_0(io_d_in_2)
);
SB_IO #(
   .PIN_TYPE(6'b011001)
) io3_iob (
   .PACKAGE_PIN(io[3]),
   .OUTPUT_ENABLE(io_oe),
   .D_OUT_0(io_pad_out[3]),
   .D_IN_0(io_d_in_3)
);
@

== Pin constraints

iCEstick pin numbers, identical to `src/spi.nw` lines 235-241 so the
same physical wires reach the MP135 `CN8` connector that the
existing qspi/mmap_spi chapters use.

<<mmap_prbs.pcf>>=
set_io clk     21
set_io cs_n    56
set_io sclk    45
set_io io[0]   47
set_io io[1]   44
set_io io[2]   60
set_io io[3]   48
@

== Test plan

Phase 2 sweeps four (presc, sshift, dlyb) operating points to
characterize the SCLK timing margin of the fabric-register +
unregistered SB_IO pad path with the new PRBS data source. Each
block is a fully self-contained test_serv submission: it programs
the bitstream, resets the MP135, flashes firmware, opens UART, sets
the operating point with `p`, runs `I 1073741824` (1 GiB twin-DDR
pass-A vs pass-B integrity using the existing baremetal `I`
command), and closes UART. The twin-DDR comparison is bit-perfect
because the PRBS slave reseeds its LFSR on every CS-fall, so pass A
and pass B receive identical PRBS streams.

The blocks are ordered safest-first per AGENTS.md regression
discipline -- run_md aborts on first failing block, so block D
(presc=4, SCLK=131 MHz, comfortable timing margin) MUST come first
to gate the mission, with blocks B/C/A characterizing what works at
presc=3 (SCLK=164 MHz, marginal). Block D's check is assertable
(`firsterr==-1 AND mbps > 400`); blocks B/C/A always pass after
recording the result so the regression continues to characterize
the full sweep when D succeeds.

The four operating points are:
- D: presc=4 sshift=0 dlyb=0 (SCLK 131 MHz, mission gate, safest)
- B: presc=3 sshift=1 dlyb=0 (SCLK 164 MHz, late-sample at master)
- C: presc=3 sshift=0 dlyb=1 unit=64 (SCLK 164 MHz, DLYB tap mid-range)
- A: presc=3 sshift=0 dlyb=0 (SCLK 164 MHz, iter-2 baseline reproducer)

<<TEST.md>>=
mmap_prbs block A1 indirect-read diagnostic at presc=5 -- probe whether the slave produces non-Hi-Z bytes when the master uses FMODE=01 (indirect). Hex dump tells us if the slave's quad-output path is alive (clean PRBS), opcode-blocked (all 0xFF), or stuck low (all 0x00). Diagnostic only; always passes after recording.

```
